is it largely
due to the drawdown of U.S.
forces?

11:35.862 --> 11:38.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID SEDNEY, Former Defense
Department Official:
It's partly due to the draw
down. I agree

11:38.731 --> 11:40.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with Barney on that.

11:40.533 --> 11:46.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Afghan forces have done very
well. But
we built a large Afghan army.
And the numbers

11:46.839 --> 11:50.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are there. And the Afghans are
willing to
fight. The big problem is, is,
we didn't put

11:50.443 --> 11:55.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the enablers that Defense
Minister Stanekzai
was talking about, air support,
helicopters,

11:55.782 --> 12:00.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
intelligence. We ripped those
out of Afghanistan
before the Afghan forces were
ready to operate

12:00.353 --> 12:02.121 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on their own.

12:02.155 --> 12:07.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we're now paying the price.
But the causes
go beyond that. The Taliban have
mounted in

12:07.493 --> 12:13.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the last two years, since we
stopped fighting,
we stopped using combat forces,
their largest

12:13.166 --> 12:18.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
offensives ever. More Afghans
are dying today
than at any time since before
2001.

12:18.104 --> 12:20.440 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: At the hands of
the Taliban?

12:20.473 --> 12:24.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID SEDNEY: At the hands of
the Taliban.
This offensive is enabled by
sanctuaries in

12:24.978 --> 12:32.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Pakistan. And it has also been
enabled by
an internecine struggle among
different Taliban

12:32.285 --> 12:37.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
factions and with a new factor
in Afghanistan,
Da'esh, the Islamic State, which
is seeking

12:37.123 --> 12:38.691 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
inroads there as well.

12:38.725 --> 12:41.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This adds all up to much more
violence and
many more deaths.

12:41.694 --> 12:46.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Barney Rubin, are
these factors
that the U.S. should have
anticipated, or

12:46.933 --> 12:53.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
did they just pop on the scene,
to everyone's
surprise, particularly the
Pakistan and the

12:53.406 --> 12:55.708 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Da'esh, or ISIS, presence?

12:55.742 --> 13:02.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARNETT RUBIN: Well, I mean, by
the U.S.,
that would be David and me and
our bosses.

13:02.982 --> 13:11.557 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think that we did
anticipate it. And
the fact is, we didn't -- you
know, the president

13:11.591 --> 13:17.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decided that the national
interest of the
United States wasn't served by
having our

13:17.864 --> 13:22.335 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
military, with all those
resources, in Afghanistan
for more than 15 years.

13:22.368 --> 13:27.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We understood that that would
mean a deterioration
of the military situation. And
that means

13:27.040 --> 13:31.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that it's more important than
ever for us
to move ahead with the
diplomatic and political

13:31.611 --> 13:35.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
solution, and also with the
investment in
regional infrastructure which is
just getting

13:35.882 --> 13:37.717 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
off the ground now.

13:37.750 --> 13:40.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Unfortunately, there were some
people in our
government who thought you could
just postpone

13:40.386 --> 13:45.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
those things until the military
option was
successful. But, of course, that
was never

13:46.025 --> 13:50.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
realistic. We're paying the
price for that
partly now, but, in fact, we
still are moving

13:50.196 --> 13:51.898 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in that direction.

13:51.931 --> 13:56.235 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And despite the serious
deterioration, the
increase in violence that David
has talked

13:56.269 --> 14:03.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about, again, bear in mind,
possibly taking
Sangin district, which you
called strategic

14:03.710 --> 14:12.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- I'm not sure why -- in
Helmand Province
is a long way from taking Kabul
or any major

14:13.019 --> 14:14.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
provincial center.

14:14.420 --> 14:17.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You mean because
of the size
and the location of it?

14:18.024 --> 14:22.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARNETT RUBIN: Yes. The Taliban
took over
Khanashin District in Helmand.
I'm not sure

14:22.662 --> 14:26.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
that any government ever
controlled Khanashin
District. It's mostly empty.

14:26.099 --> 14:31.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David Sedney,
what about the
other argument we sometimes hear
that prolonging

14:31.204 --> 14:37.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the presence of large numbers of
U.S. forces
in that part of the world, it
basically embolden

14:37.677 --> 14:43.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- it makes the other side,
whether it's the
Taliban or ISIS, want to fight
the U.S. even

14:43.049 --> 14:44.317 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
more?

14:44.350 --> 14:46.319 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID SEDNEY: Well, the last two
years have
proved that wrong.

14:46.352 --> 14:51.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, as we have withdrawn,
as Barney said
-- we had over 140,000 U.S. and
other countries'

14:51.691 --> 14:57.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
forces there two-plus years ago
-- we barely
have 10,000 there now. As those
forces have

14:57.330 --> 15:02.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
reduced, the Taliban offensive
has increased.
The Taliban use of violence has
increased

15:02.468 --> 15:04.704 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as foreign forces have
decreased.

15:04.737 --> 15:09.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it's not the question of
presence of foreign
forces. It's a question of
control and power.

15:09.308 --> 15:14.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Taliban have made clear they
want to rule
Afghanistan. When the Taliban
have taken more

15:14.447 --> 15:18.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
territory this year -- and they
have -- they
have gone out and killed civil
society people.

15:19.018 --> 15:23.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have persecuted women. They
have gone
back to exactly the same kind of
things that

15:23.356 --> 15:28.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they were doing before 2001 that
made Afghanistan
such a hellish place to live for
most Afghans.

15:28.594 --> 15:32.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Barnett
Rubin, that being
the case, what can the U.S.,
what can the

15:32.298 --> 15:35.268 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Afghan government do to counter
that?

15:35.301 --> 15:40.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARNETT RUBIN: Well, we are --
first of all,
again, to come back to David's
most important

15:40.940 --> 15:46.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
point, this is not just a
conflict between
the Taliban and the Afghan
government.

15:46.179 --> 15:51.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a regional conflict, and
particularly
the basic source of it is the
conflict between

15:51.717 --> 15:55.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Afghanistan and the state of
Pakistan. The
Taliban wouldn't be able to
mount all these

15:55.822 --> 16:00.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
offensives and so on, though
they would exist
and they would have to be dealt
with politically,

16:00.393 --> 16:03.963 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if they didn't have undisturbed
sanctuaries
in Pakistan.

16:03.996 --> 16:08.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the reasons for that, other
than Pakistan
being evil or
terrorist-supporting, Pakistan

16:08.301 --> 16:13.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has certain interests in the
region. And we
are now trying to address those
diplomatically.

16:13.573 --> 16:17.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's extremely difficulty. We
have to have
enough forces on the ground in
Afghanistan,

16:17.410 --> 16:23.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so that the situation remains
relatively stable
to give us the space to do that
diplomatic

16:23.616 --> 16:25.351 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
work.

16:25.384 --> 16:27.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're now getting much more
support in that
work from China and so on. So, I
think that

16:27.787 --> 16:35.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the focus that the media have on
the back
and forth of controlling 100
meters there

16:35.228 --> 16:39.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and 100 meters somewhere else in
different
remote parts of the country is
missing the

16:39.298 --> 16:41.067 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
point.

16:41.100 --> 16:43.836 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The main weakness on the
Afghanistan government
side is not whether their forces
can fight

16:43.870 --> 16:49.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Taliban. It's the political
divisions
within the Afghan government
which sometimes

16:49.575 --> 16:55.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
undermine the forces. And on the
other side,
the main issue is that the
Taliban's sanctuary

16:55.948 --> 16:58.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Pakistan, not how strong or
angry they
are.

16:58.684 --> 17:03.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David Sedney, how
do you see
what the U.S. and others need to
do to turn

17:03.522 --> 17:05.291 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this around?

17:05.324 --> 17:07.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID SEDNEY: I agree that the
eventual aim
is peace. And, ideally, that
would be peace

17:07.793 --> 17:12.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
talks with the Taliban. But, in
the meantime,
the Taliban offensive has to be
stopped.

17:12.064 --> 17:16.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
German Defense Minister de
Maiziere, when
she was in Afghanistan last
week, acknowledged

17:17.003 --> 17:22.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the NATO-U.S. withdrawal
had been too
hasty and ill-prepared and
pledged that Germany

17:22.208 --> 17:25.711 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would increase by over 15
percent its troops
in Afghanistan.

17:25.745 --> 17:30.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just today, Turkish Prime
Minister Erdogan,
meeting with President Ghani,
pledged that

17:30.716 --> 17:35.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Turkey would keep its military
presence and
work for peace through strength.
We need to

17:35.288 --> 17:40.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
reverse the mistakes we made in
the past and
give the Afghans the help that
Defense Minister

17:40.326 --> 17:43.129 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Stanekzai asked for earlier in
your program.

17:43.162 --> 17:46.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Otherwise, people will die well
before peace
talks have a chance to start.

17:46.766 --> 17:50.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, if 5,500
troops into 2017
is not enough, what is the right
number?

17:50.670 --> 17:53.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID SEDNEY: There's no real
right number.
It's right capabilities.

17:53.506 --> 17:57.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We don't need combat troops
there. We need
the enablers that Defense
Minister Stanekzai

17:57.576 --> 18:03.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
asked for. The Afghans need air
support, intelligence
support, the logistics support
and well-trained

18:03.783 --> 18:08.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
advisers. A few years ago, we
disbanded the
group that the Army had -- the
U.S. Army had

18:08.621 --> 18:12.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
created to train people on how
to build other
countries' armies.

18:12.425 --> 18:16.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we're now sending advisers
to Afghanistan
who just, unfortunately, don't
know what they're

18:16.562 --> 18:20.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
doing. We need to give the
Afghans the help
they need. They're ready to
fight. We don't

18:20.499 --> 18:23.035 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
need combat troops. But they do
need our help.

18:23.069 --> 18:27.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We appreciate
your perspective,
both of you, at the end of this
year.

18:27.640 --> 18:38.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
David Sedney, Barnett Rubin,
thank you.

18:38.584 --> 18:49.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The Iran hostage
crisis was one
of the defining moments of the
1970s, and

18:49.795 --> 18:54.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it fractured a relationship
between two nations
that has never healed.

18:54.100 --> 19:02.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, 36 years after it began,
the former hostages
are finally getting
compensation. It was November

19:02.908 --> 19:11.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
4, 1979. The U.S. Embassy in
Tehran was overrun
by militant Iranian students.
Eventually,

19:11.350 --> 19:17.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
53 American hostages, many of
them diplomats,
were held. Some were paraded
around, exposed

19:17.990 --> 19:23.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to mock firing squads and
beatings. Some were
placed in solitary confinement.
They were

19:23.829 --> 19:31.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
held 444 days, as the nation
watched and waited.
One major rescue attempt failed.

19:31.470 --> 19:38.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fifty-two were released on
January 20, 1981,
just as Ronald Reagan was being
sworn in.

19:38.744 --> 19:42.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One other hostage was released
earlier because
of illness.

19:42.815 --> 19:48.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Their families celebrated. But
the crisis
helped end Jimmy Carter's
presidency and led

19:48.521 --> 19:54.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to a three-decade-plus rupture
between Iran
and the United States. And for
many of the

19:54.860 --> 20:01.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
former captives, the ordeal left
a lasting
toll, including depression. But,
until now,

20:01.033 --> 20:06.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
they have received no
compensation for the
ordeal. The massive spending
legislation passed

20:06.705 --> 20:14.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by Congress last week changes
that, awarding
each hostage $10,000 for each
day of captivity.

20:14.380 --> 20:20.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The settlement also provides the
potential
for compensation for victims of
other incidents,

20:21.020 --> 20:26.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
including the 1998 U.S. Embassy
bombings in
East Africa and the 9/11
attacks.

20:26.792 --> 20:30.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
David Herszenhorn of The New
York Times has
been combing through this
settlement and speaking

20:30.429 --> 20:33.199 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with former hostages. He joins
me now.

20:33.232 --> 20:36.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
David, how much money in total
are we talking
about here?

20:36.235 --> 20:38.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN, The New York
Times: Well,
we actually don't know yet,
because some of

20:38.904 --> 20:43.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the money depends on court cases
that are
ongoing and judgments that have
already handed

20:43.409 --> 20:46.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
down in the courts, where there
may be awards.
They haven't been paid yet.

20:46.779 --> 20:50.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, the Supreme Court will
soon, next
month, be hearing a case about
this. But we're

20:50.783 --> 20:58.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
starting out with a pot of
roughly $4 billion,
a big chunk of which goes to 911
victims,

20:58.491 --> 21:02.328 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
$1 billion of which will go to
the Iran hostages.

21:02.361 --> 21:06.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: You mentioned the
Supreme Court.
Hasn't this very thing been
litigated before?

21:06.532 --> 21:10.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Has it gone as far as the
Supreme Court and
said, no, there will be no
compensation?

21:10.136 --> 21:11.904 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN: Well, that's
right.

21:11.937 --> 21:16.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What we have now is basically a
congressional
judgment. The Iran hostages were
denied at

21:16.442 --> 21:21.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
every turn, in large part
because the agreement
that secured their release known
as the Algiers

21:21.881 --> 21:28.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Accord barred them from seeking
any compensation.
So the courts repeatedly
rejected any claims,

21:28.387 --> 21:32.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
citing this treaty effectively
in 1981 that
secured their release.

21:32.057 --> 21:37.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What Congress has done is step
in with legislative
relief and said, Congress is
basically giving

21:37.062 --> 21:39.031 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to them the equivalent of a
court judgment.

21:39.064 --> 21:40.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Right.

21:40.866 --> 21:43.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN: And now, with
this bigger
group of victims, they each have
their claim,

21:43.335 --> 21:47.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what some victims may have been
awarded in
court, what the Iran hostages
were awarded

21:47.540 --> 21:51.911 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by the Congress, and a special
master will
dole out the money that exists.

21:51.944 --> 21:56.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It starts with a big chunk of a
settlement,
really a landmark fine, penalty
paid by the

21:56.849 --> 22:02.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bank BNP Paribas, which had
violated sanctions
against Iran, Sudan, and Cuba.

22:02.454 --> 22:05.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So the pot of money
that this
is coming from, even though it's
in a budget

22:05.824 --> 22:07.560 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bill, is not really coming from
the budget?

22:07.593 --> 22:09.428 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN: That's right.

22:09.461 --> 22:15.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This was one of the political
tools in crafting
this settlement, in making this
possible,

22:15.301 --> 22:19.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that there was a ready and
available pot of
money that didn't have to come
right out of

22:19.939 --> 22:21.607 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
taxpayers' pockets, so to speak.

22:21.640 --> 22:24.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And it also didn't
come out of
the Iranian government's pocket
either.

22:24.376 --> 22:27.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN: And that's
been some disappointment
to some of the hostages, who
really do feel

22:27.780 --> 22:31.083 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that Iran ought to pay for what
happened directly.

22:31.116 --> 22:36.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, sanctions had a
role. Did
the nuclear negotiations that we
watched so

22:36.488 --> 22:37.489 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
closely have a role?

22:37.523 --> 22:39.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN: There's no
question.

22:39.258 --> 22:45.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As the nuclear accord was being
developed,
Congress certainly got much more
involved,

22:45.764 --> 22:49.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was paying much more attention
to the idea
that the relationship between
the United States

22:49.768 --> 22:52.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and Iran was going to begin to
thaw, that
sanctions might be eased. And
there were many

22:52.871 --> 22:56.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people, hostages included, who
said, wait
a minute, we're not comfortable
with this

22:56.809 --> 23:01.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
relationship thawing when we
haven't addressed
the reason, one could say, it
ruptured in

23:01.847 --> 23:05.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the first place, or a big part
of the reason,
that defining moment, as they
say, in the

23:05.851 --> 23:08.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
1970s, where the embassy is
overrun.

23:08.120 --> 23:13.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Why did this also
include victims
of other attacks? Why not just
keep it specifically

23:13.926 --> 23:15.761 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to Iran?

23:15.794 --> 23:19.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN: Well, that's
a political
question, but also one of
fairness and equity

23:19.531 --> 23:22.301 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think in the minds of some of
the lawmakers.

23:22.334 --> 23:26.839 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Iran has been accused of
sponsoring terror
in many different locations on
many different

23:26.872 --> 23:33.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
occasions. Victims and family
members of victims
of the two bombings in Beirut,
1983-'84, trucking

23:33.412 --> 23:39.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bombing killed Marines and
others, are included
here. And there has been
difficulty, even

23:39.752 --> 23:43.255 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for the victims who have been
able to pursue
their claims in court.

23:43.289 --> 23:47.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Winning a judgment has been
possible for a
number of victims, but getting
paid has not

23:47.993 --> 23:51.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been possible, because, of
course, Iran is
not coming up with money. There
was one rare

23:51.630 --> 23:55.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
instance where Libya was looking
to get back
into the good graces of the rest
of the world

23:55.934 --> 23:57.136 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and was willing to pay
compensation.

23:57.169 --> 23:58.070 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: But this is
different.

23:58.103 --> 23:59.838 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN: That's right.

23:59.872 --> 24:02.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, here, they really had to
come up with
a solution where some of these
folks would

24:02.675 --> 24:10.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
see some payback after, you
know, losing loved
ones or having been injured
themselves, because

24:10.115 --> 24:13.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the court decision was just
that. It was just
a number on paper, but there was
no money

24:13.786 --> 24:15.621 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
behind it.

24:15.654 --> 24:18.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: You talked to some
of these surviving
hostages after -- in the course
of writing

24:18.957 --> 24:23.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the story about the settlement.
How have they
reacted? It's been a long time.

24:23.429 --> 24:28.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN: They are
exhausted, is
one word. Certainly, there's a
very big mix

24:28.600 --> 24:30.502 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of emotions.

24:30.536 --> 24:33.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some are quite satisfied,
they're quite relieved,
quite grateful to Congress for
not forgetting

24:33.772 --> 24:37.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about them. Many of them felt
forgotten really
until the movie "Argo" came out.
And "Argo"

24:37.076 --> 24:40.012 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wasn't even about their case. It
was about
six folks who had escaped.

24:40.045 --> 24:42.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The Ben Affleck
movie that won
the Oscar a couple of years ago.

24:42.915 --> 24:44.783 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN: That's right.

24:44.817 --> 24:47.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They felt that that renewed
attention. But,
until then, they really had a
sense that younger

24:47.920 --> 24:51.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people, it's not something in
their memory.
This is something that was
really forgotten.

24:51.623 --> 24:57.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, they were also
outraged by
Benghazi, where yet again
diplomatic personnel

24:57.696 --> 25:01.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
working for the United States
government in
dangerous places overseas were
put at risk.

25:01.934 --> 25:05.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, there's a sense of closure
for some of
them. Many said it was too soon
to see know

25:05.104 --> 25:10.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
exactly how they feel about it.
But the comment
that struck me the most, Barry
Rosen, who

25:10.876 --> 25:15.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was a press attache -- he's a
New Yorker -- said,
"I really don't want to talk
about it." He

25:15.481 --> 25:17.216 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
said, "We have been through
enough."

25:17.249 --> 25:20.152 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And that seemed to be a
sentiment I think
all of them can agree on. They
went through

25:20.185 --> 25:21.887 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
enough.

25:21.920 --> 25:24.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Well, nearly four
decades later,
it probably feels like more than
enough.

25:24.123 --> 25:27.526 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
David Herszenhorn of The New
York Times, thank
you for this.

25:27.559 --> 25:33.532 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID HERSZENHORN: You're
welcome.

25:33.565 --> 25:41.073 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

25:41.106 --> 25:47.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
gifts to cure
bad habits; the subtleties that
